{
  "id": "001.5",
  "title": "Present Simple – To Be – Positive",
  "topic": "Present Simple",
  "subtopic": "To Be – Positive",
  "description": "How to use am, is, and are in positive Present Simple sentences",
  "lessons": [
    {
      "id": "001.5-lesson-1",
      "title": "Positive Structure with To Be",
      "content": "**Structure:** Subject + **am / is / are**\n\nUse **am** with **I**.\nUse **is** with **he / she / it** and singular nouns.\nUse **are** with **you / we / they** and plural nouns.\n\n| Subject | To be | Example |\n|---------|-------|---------|\n| I | am | I am happy. |\n| You | are | You are happy. |\n| We | are | We are happy. |\n| They | are | They are happy. |\n| He | is | He is happy. |\n| She | is | She is happy. |\n| It | is | It is happy. |"
    },
    {
      "id": "001.5-lesson-2",
      "title": "When We Use To Be",
      "content": "We use **to be** before nouns, adjectives, locations, and time expressions.\n\n| Use | Example |\n|-----|---------|\n| Noun | I am a doctor. |\n| Adjective | She is smart. |\n| Location | We are at home. |\n| Time | The party is at 9. |\n\n📌 Use **am / is / are** when you describe what someone or something **is**, **where** it is, or **when** it is."
    },
    {
      "id": "001.5-lesson-3",
      "title": "Common Mistakes",
      "content": "⚠️ Do not leave out the verb **to be**.\n⚠️ Do not add an extra pronoun after the subject.\n⚠️ Match the verb to the subject correctly: **I am**, **he/she/it is**, **you/we/they are**.\n\n| Incorrect | Correct |\n|-----------|---------|\n| Israel she very small. | Israel is very small. |\n| John he is a doctor. | John is a doctor. |\n| I tall. | I am tall. |\n| The children they smart. | The children are smart. |"
    }
  ],
